  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: d1d62931ab01cd14b84145ae3bdd017f, type: 3}
  m_Name: Chapter 5
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  chapter: 5
  levelTerms:
  - level: 19
    terms:
    - term: Center of Mass
      unit: 
      type: 0
      description: It is position relative to the object or system
      details: "Maybe you did, in science shows, or maybe in documentaries on TV.
        You may have even noticed, oreven saw it in action -- it's just that you\u2019ve
        never known that it was called as such."
    - term: Momentum
      unit: 
      type: 0
      description: Amount of motion an object has, referred to as mass in motion,
        it is a vector value
      details: Suppose we have an object moving at a certain amount of velocity,
        with a certain amount of mass. This object moves really fast, thus we can
        safely assume that it has energy, and will do a very high amount of work
        to something it might come across with. But, what we donot notice is that
        the object is also gaining another value.
  - level: 21
    terms:
    - term: Impulse
      unit: 
      type: 0
      description: Force in time, associated with momentum
      details: "That equation right there shows that a change in momentum is equal
        to a change in force exerted within a certain time. It is certainly related
        to momentum, but in some ways, it isn\u2019t. This equation is used in the
        study of an average force being applied onto a system. We can always compute
        for momentum readily if we have velocity and mass, which are readily available.
        But, if we only have time, we have to yet determine the strength of the object
        upon contact. This is why we have impulse"
    - term: Specific Impulse
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Measurement used to determine efficacy of rocket propellants,
        used in rocket science
      details: Suppose we have an object moving at a certain amount of velocity,
        with a certain amount of mass. This object moves really fast, thus we can
        safely assume that it has energy, and will do a very high amount of work
        to something it might come across with. But, what we donot notice is that
        the object is also gaining another value.
    - term: Collision
      unit: 
      type: 0
      description: Direct application of momentum and impulse
      details: We all have seen it in the news, in TV, and even in movies, and written
        and illustrated works. We usually associate it with vehicular accidents,
        because these are examples of this concept at work. If an object has momentum,
        and demonstrates impulse before impact, the moment that object impacts with
        another object, the object is demonstrating collision
    - term: Elastic Collision
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Each bounce conserve less and less energy due to force being weaker
        with each succeeding bounce, until it stops
      details: The best way to describe this type of collision is a ball bouncing
        off the floor. Sure, the ball will bounce upon hitting the ground, and it
        will conserve momentum and energy. But, each bounce will conserve less and
        less energy due to the force being weaker with each succeeding bounce, until
        it will stop altogether. This kind of elastic collision is called a contact
        collision, and is not a perfect collision. The other type, which is noncontact
        collision, is almost perfect. The noncontact collision is a kind of elastic
        collision where the objects interact with each other, even without direct
        contact. A perfect example would be a planet slinging a space shuttle in
        another direction.
    - term: Inelastic Collision
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Occurs often because energy is lost more than conserved
      details: There is another kind of collision, in which if the targetdoes not
        bend to the force generated by the incoming projectile, the said target will
        move alongside the already-moving object, or the two interacting objects
        will stick together, if enough force and momentum is generated.
    - term: Coefficient of Restitution
      unit: 
      type: 2
      description: Shows ratio between objects before and after impact
      details: "This coefficient shows the ratio between objects before and after
        impact. \n\nCOR = Vf\r\n      V0"
